USER:
I crushed my session today! I feel incredible!

CONTEXT:
- Readiness: Green (Productive)
- Session: Z4 "3x8min Z4 / 4min Z1"
- Sport: cycling
- Level: intermediate
- Phase: build

[KNOWLEDGE]

Indoor training has one nemesis: heat. Without the natural cooling of wind passing over you, your core temperature climbs and power drops. Most cyclists see their indoor FTP run 5 to 10 percent lower than outdoors, even when fitness is identical.

You have two options. First, you can set a separate indoor FTP at about 90 to 95 percent of your outdoor number and train to those zones. This keeps the relative effort honest. Second—and this is what I'd recommend—get serious about cooling.

Your workout structure gets chosen based on your training phase, experience level, and available time. Same zone, different structures—and that's by design.

Two athletes both doing Zone 4 threshold work might get very different sessions. A beginner in base phase might do three 8-minute intervals with four minutes rest between—shorter intervals, more recovery.

[INTERPRETER]
{"action": "explain", "question": "Celebrating a great session", "free_text": "I crushed my session today! I feel incredible!"}

JOSI:
That's what it feels like when the hard work pays off — your body was ready, your effort was right, and the session did exactly what it was supposed to. Enjoy this feeling. Now take care of recovery so the next session is just as good. You earned it.
